{"title":"Negative Indexing","markdown":{"headingText":"Negative Indexing","headingAttr":{"id":"sec-negative-indexing","classes":[],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-problem}\n**The Problem**\n\nYour supervisor tells you: \"Actually, participant #1 was a pilot test entry from before the study officially started — exclude that one row from all your calculations, but keep the other 99.\" You know how to pull *specific* elements out of a vector using positive indexing, but now you need the opposite: everything *except* one particular position.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mission}\n**Your Mission**\n\nExclude one or more elements from a vector by position, rather than selecting elements to include.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-think}\n**Think Before Coding**\n\n- If positive numbers inside `[ ]` mean \"give me these positions,\" what might the opposite sign mean?\n- If you needed to exclude both the 1st and 2nd elements, how might you extend a single negative index to several?\n:::\n\n## The R Concept\n\nPutting a **minus sign** in front of a position inside `[ ]` tells R to exclude that position, returning everything else:\n\n```r\nx[-position]\n```\n\n```r\nages <- c(46, 53, 59, 49, 61)\nages[-1]        # everything except the 1st element\nages[-c(1, 2)]  # everything except the 1st and 2nd elements\n```\n\nThis mirrors positive indexing exactly, just inverted — and it composes with everything you learned on the last page, including ranges: `ages[-(1:5)]` excludes the first five elements.\n\n## Demonstration\n\n```r\nages <- c(46, 53, 59, 49, 61, 18, 62, 68, 33, 36)\n\nages[-1]\n```\n\n```\n[1] 53 59 49 61 18 62 68 33 36\n```\n\n```r\nages[-c(1, 2)]\n```\n\n```\n[1] 59 49 61 18 62 68 33 36\n```\n\n```r\nages[-(1:3)]\n```\n\n```\n[1] 49 61 18 62 68 33 36\n```\n\n## Explore\n\nTry mixing signs: `ages[c(-1, 2)]`. What happens? R will refuse and produce an error — predict what that error might say before you run it, based on the idea that \"include position 2\" and \"exclude position 1\" are contradictory instructions to combine in one call.\n\n## Solve the Problem\n\n```r\nparticipants <- read.csv(\"data/participants.csv\")\n\n# Exclude participant 1 (the pilot test entry) from the age calculation\nvalid_ages <- participants$age[-1]\n\nlength(valid_ages)\n```\n\n```\n[1] 99\n```\n\n```r\nmean(valid_ages, na.rm = TRUE)\n```\n\n```\n[1] 47.36735\n```\n\n## Interpret the Result\n\n`valid_ages` now holds 99 values instead of 100, correctly excluding the pilot test entry, and the mean age recalculated on this corrected set is 47.4 years (rounded) — very close to, but not identical to, the full-sample mean from Level 1, since removing one participant necessarily shifts the average slightly.\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mistake}\n**Common Mistakes**\n\n- **Mixing positive and negative indices in one call.** `x[c(-1, 2)]` produces an error (`can't mix positive and negative subscripts`) — you must choose one approach or the other for a single indexing operation.\n- **Forgetting parentheses around a range you want to negate.** `-1:3` is interpreted as \"the sequence from −1 to 3,\" not \"exclude positions 1 through 3\" — you need `-(1:3)` with explicit parentheses to negate the whole range.\n- **Assuming negative indexing modifies the original vector.** `ages[-1]` returns a *new* vector with one element excluded; it does not delete anything from `ages` itself unless you explicitly reassign the result back: `ages <- ages[-1]`.\n:::\n\n## Practice Problem\n\nUsing `participants$bmi`, create a vector `bmi_excluding_first_three` that excludes the first three participants' BMI values, using negative indexing with a range.\n\n## Challenge Problem\n\nYour supervisor now says participants #1 and #100 were both pilot test entries — exclude both from `participants$age` in a single line of negative indexing, and compute the mean of the remaining 98 ages.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- A negative sign inside `[ ]` excludes that position (or positions) rather than selecting it.\n- Positive and negative indices cannot be mixed in a single indexing call.\n- Indexing (positive or negative) returns a new vector — it doesn't modify the original unless you explicitly reassign the result.\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-check}\n**Knowledge Check**\n\n1. **Multiple choice.** What does `x[-2]` return for `x <- c(10, 20, 30)`?\n   a) `20`\n   b) `c(10, 30)`\n   c) `c(20, 30)`\n   d) An error\n\n2. **True or false.** `x[c(-1, 2)]` is valid R code that excludes position 1 and includes position 2.\n\n3. **Predict the output.**\n   ```r\n   x <- c(5, 10, 15, 20, 25)\n   x[-(1:2)]\n   ```\n\n4. **Find the error.**\n   ```r\n   x[-1:3]\n   ```\n\n<details class=\"pbl-answer\">\n<summary>Show answers</summary>\n\n1. **b)** `c(10, 30)` — position 2 (`20`) is excluded.\n2. **False.** Mixing positive and negative indices in the same call raises an error.\n3. `[1] 15 20 25`\n4. Without parentheses, `-1:3` is read as the sequence from −1 to 3, not \"exclude 1 through 3.\" It should be `x[-(1:3)]`.\n\n</details>\n:::\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":"auto","echo":true,"output":true,"warning":false,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"message":false,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env":null,"code-fold":false,"code-overflow":"scroll","code-link":true,"code-line-numbers":false,"code-tools":true,"tbl-colwidths":"auto","merge-includes":true,"inline-includes":false